Toxic shock syndrome: This is a rare but serious condition caused by bacteria that release toxins into the bloodstream. Symptoms can include a sudden high fever, rash, low blood pressure, and shock.
Kawasaki disease: This is a rare disease that causes inflammation of the blood vessels. Symptoms can include a high fever, rash, swollen glands, and red eyes.
Rocky Mountain spotted fever: This is a bacterial infection that is spread by ticks. Symptoms can include a high fever, headache, muscle aches, and a rash.
Scarlet fever: This is a bacterial infection that is spread by contact with an infected person. Symptoms can include a sore throat, fever, and a rash.

Drug reaction: This is a reaction to a medication that can cause a variety of symptoms, including a rash. Common medications that can cause a rash include antibiotics, anticonvulsants, and pain relievers.
Viral exanthem: This is a rash caused by a virus. Common viral exanthems include chickenpox, measles, and rubella.
Secondary syphilis: This is a stage of syphilis that can cause a rash. Other symptoms of secondary syphilis include swollen lymph nodes, joint pain, and hair loss.
Pityriasis rosea: This is a common skin condition that causes a scaly, salmon-colored rash. It is usually not serious and goes away on its own within a few weeks.
Eczema: This is a chronic skin condition that causes dry, itchy skin. There are many different types of eczema, and the symptoms can vary.
Psoriasis: This is a chronic skin condition that causes thick, scaly plaques of skin. It is not contagious, but it can be uncomfortable and embarrassing.
